title: Assystem: benefits from two positive analyses
full_text: The share price is up nearly 1.5% on the back of two positive analyses published today.Stifel reaffirms its 'buy' recommendation on Assystem and raises its target price from 50 to 55 euros, following the engineering consultancy's announcement of first-quarter 2023 sales 9% ahead of expectations.'Also, taking this into account, we are slightly raising our forecasts for 2023. In addition, we are increasing EPS by 6.6% to also take into account a higher contribution from the results of Expleo, 38%-owned by Assystem', says the broker.Invest Securities confirms its buy rating on Assystem shares, with a price target raised from €54 to €55. The analyst believes that the 16.4% rise in 1st-quarter sales illustrates the message conveyed by management in mid-March on the occasion of the 2022 results, namely that 'the acceleration in growth would be faster than initially envisaged'.  Given that the main bottleneck, recruitment, is also being managed fairly well (25% of recruitment planned for 2023 was completed in Q1), momentum is indeed improving in consolidated activities", the research house points out.Invest Securities now believes that 'the only uncertainty lies in the timing of the disposal of the Expleo and Framatome stakes', but stresses that 'more than ever, Assystem remains a strong conviction to take advantage of the nuclear revival'.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. All rights reserved.

title: STMICRO :  Oddo BHF raises its target on the stock
full_text: Oddo BHF confirms its 'outperform' rating on STMicro shares, with its target price raised from €58 to €60. Yesterday, the stock was heckled on the stock market (-8.7% in Paris), despite very good results, a reaction that Oddo BHF felt was 'very exaggerated', especially as the lowered outlook for second-half gross margin (MB) was already known.  The main reason [for this drop] is the fear of a slowdown in the market and a reversal in the price dynamic, which until now has supported margins", says the analyst, who nevertheless points out that "beyond this one-off drop, the Group is still targeting an MB of 50%, based on sales of $20 billion by 2025/27".With sales coming in at $4.25 bn, slightly above consensus at $4.2 bn, up 19.8% yoy and down 4% qoq vs. a guidance of -5.1%, Oddo BHF is raising its 2023 EPS by 4%. title: Investor flight from Verbio after lowered annual outlook
full_text: FRANKFURT (dpa-AFX Broker) - The already long-lasting slide of Verbio shares intensified again on Friday. The previous day, they had already reacted in late trading with significant losses to the fact that the annual outlook was lowered due to the decline in prices for biodiesel and higher costs. Now the share price slumped again by almost 13 percent to 30.50 euros. That marked the lowest level since March 2021, and the shares are by far the worst performer in the SDax small-cap index, down by about half for the year.      According to a statement on Thursday, the company expects an operating profit (Ebitda) of only 240 million euros in fiscal 2022/23. Previously, the target had been 300 million euros. It did not help on Friday that analysts reacted relatively calmly. Stifel expert Adrian Pehl described the warning in a study as not unexpected and Deutsche Bank analyst Niklas Becker considers the long-term story to be intact. Despite cuts, the two experts remain with price targets of at least 50 euros well above the current price./tih/jha/----------------------- dpa-AFX Broker - Trader News from dpa-AFX-----------------------

title: DASSAULT SYSTÈMES :  Berenberg downgrades its recommendation
full_text: Berenberg announced on Thursday that it had downgraded its recommendation on Dassault Systèmes from 'buy' to 'hold', with a price target reduced from €41.5 to €38.5.In a research note, the analyst explains that the first-quarter results published by the French computer-aided design and manufacturing software group fell short of expectations.In particular, Berenberg expresses concern about weaker-than-expected license sales, calling into question the resilience of the company's business model, as well as the scenario of a turnaround in business by the end of the year.The intermediary also rules out any potential improvement in profitability due to the weakness of license sales, which generate high profit margins, and the sustained pace of hiring.Pending any new elements likely to support the share, the professional is downgrading its advice in the absence of any favorable catalyst on the horizon.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: TELEPERFORMANCE :  Stifel downgrades its recommendation

title: ALTEN :  Invest Securities adjusts its target
full_text: Invest Securities maintains its 'neutral' rating on Alten shares, with a slightly reduced target price, from €148 to €146.While the company reported a 14.4% increase in sales in Q1, the CFO specified that organic growth should exceed +10% in 2023. This fact prompts the analyst to raise his expectations (+1.6% at the level of 2023-25th NBI). Invest also points out that Alten's quality is well established and that market conditions remain favorable, 'particularly in the automotive, aerospace and defense sectors'.  On the other hand, M&A is unlikely to provide support in the short term, with fierce competition from PE funds reducing opportunities and limiting Alten to small-scale acquisitions (< 50mE in sales)' adds the analyst, who is therefore revising his target downwards, despite the slight increase in his expectations.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: Memscap: first-quarter results above expectations
full_text: Memscap, a manufacturer of high-precision sensors, reported above-expectation results for the first quarter on Thursday, boosted in particular by the dynamism of its aerospace business.The Grenoble-based group's share price rose by 10% following this publication, bringing its year-to-date increase to over 130%.Its consolidated sales from continuing operations came to 3.7 million euros in the first three months of the year, compared with 2.3 million a year earlier, an increase of 60.8%.Its quarterly EBITDA came to 741,000 euros, compared with 266,000 euros in Q1 2022, for an operating profit of 505 thousand euros, compared with a profit of 31.000 euros a year earlier.In a reaction note, Euroland analysts refer to "spectacular" growth and figures well above their expectations.The brokerage firm, which reiterates its buy recommendation on the stock, indicates that it has raised its target price on the stock from 4.15 to 5.10 euros.Despite the sharp rise in its share price, Euroland says it considers current levels to be an attractive entry point in view of the company's growth and profitability prospects.Memscap manufactures high-precision, high-stability pressure sensors for the aerospace and medical sectors, as well as variable attenuators (VOA) for optical communications.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. All rights reserved.

title: Takeover plan weighs on Deutsche Börse in pre-market trading
full_text: FRANKFURT (dpa-AFX Broker) - The planned billion-euro takeover of data provider Simcorp is throwing a spanner in the works for Deutsche Börse investors on Thursday. The results, which the exchange operator had presented the previous evening after the close of the stock exchange and initially convinced investors, thus receded into the background. In Tradegate trading, the shares were down 1.1 percent compared with the Xetra closing price on the previous day. In off-market trading yesterday evening, the shares were already up almost two percent at their peak.      One trader stressed that the first quarter results had initially been strong, but then took a negative view of the takeover announcement because of the valuation and the financing conditions required for it. Compared to Simcorp's closing price the previous day, which was 529 Danish kroner, the exchange operator is paying a 39 percent premium at 735 kroner. In the first quarter, Deutsche Börse had continued to benefit from brisk trading on the equity and commodity markets and higher interest rates. Thanks to the strong start, the Group is now somewhat more optimistic about the current year./tih/stk----------------------- dpa-AFX Broker - Trader News from dpa-AFX-----------------------

title: Quarterly figures help Deutsche Bank to get going
full_text: FRANKFURT (dpa-AFX) - Deutsche Bank's recently weakening share price is getting a boost on Thursday from the institution's quarterly figures. In Tradegate trading, the securities gained 1.4 percent in pre-market compared to the Xetra closing price to 9.69 euros.      At first glance, the past quarter was better than expected, said a trader. He also referred to planned share buybacks and more significant cost reductions than initially communicated.      The shares had recently come under renewed pressure as the crisis at US regional banks flared up again and slipped below ten euros. They are currently still trading below this level, but in Xetra trading could again exceed the 21-day line for the short-term trend.      JPMorgan analyst Kian Abouhossein called the figures nevertheless mixed. He said corporate banking was strong, but investment banking and retail banking were weaker than expected. The focus is also likely to be on customer outflows.      In the U.S., the troubled regional bank First Rebublic had reported this week on a large withdrawal of customer funds in the first quarter, whereupon the share price had plunged by 65 percent within two days./ajx/stk

title: TELEPERFORMANCE :  Oddo BHF lowers its target price
full_text: Oddo BHF maintains its 'outperform' rating on Teleperformance shares, with a price target reduced from 390 to 354 euros, 'due to the adjustment of the risk premium/risk-free rate (discount rate 8.4% vs. 8%)', says the analyst.Last night, the Group reported Q1 sales of 2006 million euros, up 2.2% but slightly below Oddo BHF (2036 ME) and consensus (2057 ME) estimates."Most of the difference with estimates is due to the dilutive impact on sales of the ramp-up of offshore activities (impact -0.6pt; see below)", stresses the research firm. In addition, Teleperformance management has slightly adjusted its expectations for the full year, indicating that it expects organic sales growth of around +7% (vs. over 7% initially), while the MOP target has been raised to 16% (vs. 15.7% previously).  All in all, the guidance adjustment for 2023 is rather neutral on our EPS. The adjustment of -2.2% on average over 2023-2024 is linked to an unfavorable currency effect (USD)', concludes Oddo BHF. title: KERING :  Invest Securities remains 'neutral' and raises its target
full_text: Invest Securities maintains its 'neutral' rating on Kering shares, with a price target raised from 569 to 575 euros, pointing out that 'in the luxury sector, it's only momentum that guides preferences, regardless of valuation'. According to the analyst, in a context where investors remain deaf to risks such as the euro's recovery, it's not surprising that Kering remains modestly valued in relative terms."Kering's problem is that it is confronted with factors that are specific to it, including a relaunch of the Gucci brand that has yet to be promoted, mistakes in Balenciaga's marketing that are difficult to admit, and a certain loss of steam at BV and YSL", judges Invest. Conversely, Kering's peers are riding on 'impressive momentum', which leads the analyst to wonder whether LV, Christian Dior and Hermes are not benefiting from direct transfers of market share. In the meantime, 2023 is likely to be, at best, a transitional year for Kering, with a heightened downside sensitivity factor should the economy deteriorate, which we believe is likely in the USA, if not in Europe", concludes the analyst.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: VALEO :  Invest Securities remains positive following sales figures
full_text: While adjusting its target price from 31.3 to 30.6 euros, Invest Securities reaffirms its "buy" opinion on Valeo "still justified by the low multiples", adding that the stock remains its favorite for 2023 among equipment manufacturers.After solid first-quarter 2023 sales, in line with expectations, and order intake of four billion euros in the first quarter alone for the PTS branch, guidance is unchanged, albeit with a positive bias", notes the analyst.  The acceleration already suggested for the second quarter and second half seems likely, and EBITA margin could take off beyond the 2023 guidance. But we'll have to wait a little longer before raising our profitability 'ambitions'," he continues.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: SFPI GROUP  :  Disappointing 2022 heralds a more tightly managed ship
full_text:
Disappointing 2022 heralds a more tightly managed shipEARNINGS/SALES RELEASESSFPI’s FY2022 disappointed. While it firmly stuck to its top-line objectives, margins were squeezed by fast(er) rising costs and a €4m mighty provisioning for a refoundation of its MAC division (windows, awnings, etc.). Accelerated capex is to follow. Earnings dropped by c. a third to €22m. We were banking on €26.8m. While management confirms its entrepreneurial skills (more capex, a stream of useful acquisitions, proactive deployment of ESG metrics), our 2023 earnings expectations need to be trimmed.FACTSFPI published a net profit down 33% on sales up 10.5%, or 7% pro forma. The following table provides the detail with discussion in the Analysis section below.
Despite a sharply-contracting FCF generation (on account of working capital needs), the balance sheet remains remarkably healthy with a €25m net cash position.
Dividend is trimmed to €0.05 from €0.08 in 2021 to reflect lower earnings.ANALYSISIn a summary analysis, SFPI’s earnings gave way to higher materials costs (gross margin down to 57.4% from 59.5%) and a €4m one-off to rejig the MAC business. The payroll looks comparably under control.
The gross margin erosion is above our mid-year expectations and somewhat at odds with the ongoing talk of (admittedly much larger) capital goods and construction materials stocks. Ergo, SFPI’s bargaining power is less. Its MAC division notably suffered a 4% drop in its gross margin to 52.4%. There is only so much that one can expect to pass through to consumers.
The €4m provision aimed at rethinking MAC’s industrial operations covers an inside-out review of the 11 industrial sites to optimise productivity, logistics and working conditions. This will be complemented by faster capex plans up to 2025. This rejigging of industrial assets strikes us as indicative of SFPI tightening up of its management of of its industrial assets, with upgrades to industrial tools and working practices now required to defend margins. Productivity gains can be substantial as the MAC industrial set-up was not optimal.  Underlying markets for MAC (housing renovation, amply subsidised) do not seem to be an issue. However pro forma sales up 10% have been driven by prices, indicating that end markets may not accept much more and that indeed MAC needs to work on its costs. Separately, it may be that the discretionary bit of MAC’s offer (blinds, awnings) starts to feel even more the pressure of households’ tighter pockets.
Other divisions fared comparably a bit better. DOM (everything about locks) wrote down assets for €3.7m but continued to invest in new technologies such as cloud-based access control. On the industrial front, Neu-JFK (HVAC systems for air cleaning) made brisk business out of heat exchangers that were sought after in the energy crisis. MMD (heat exchangers and sterilisation (pasteurisation) lines) also held its turf well and closed the year with still very strong orderbooks.
Balance sheet: only a bit less comfortable
SFPI is driven utterly cautiously, and rightly so. The surge in working capital requirement, in capex and an eroding EBITDA have bitten sharply into the net cash position which retreats to €25m vs. €75m a year earlier. This was bound to happen as SFPI had to pay up or shut up vis a vis suppliers which not only raised prices above their own inflation but also argued that they were short of goods. Hopefully, such excesses on the part of suppliers will be down. As a reminder, higher prices do inflate inventories too and bite in working capital terms.IMPACTThe FY2022 management comments suggest that the company is on a strong footing but will firm up that footing even more by investing more heavily into a simpler industrial set-up where needed, in spite of the near-term cash costs. AlphaValue tends to hold a positive view of businesses with a keen eye on preparing for their future. A methodological group approach to ESG matters seems to have helped unveil corners of the business which could do with upgrades. This may lead the small industrial conglomerate to move on to tigher management of its assets, i.e. with a keener search for synergies. It is unlikely to be anything but positive. In the meantime, our forecasts clearly need to be trimmed for 2023 by c. 15%.

title: Deutsche Börse back in record mode - hope for good figures
full_text: FRANKFURT (dpa-AFX Broker) - Deutsche Börse shares resumed their record chase on Tuesday. After taking a breather at the beginning of the week, they reached an all-time high of 186.15 euros in the afternoon.       Most recently, the stock exchange operator's shares were among the biggest gainers on the Dax, gaining 1.5 percent to 185.65 euros, benefiting from hopes of solid business figures. The German benchmark index slipped slightly.      Deutsche Börse will present its quarterly figures after close of trading on Wednesday. Analysts expect another strong quarter. The company is on track to achieve its targets, they said.       Bank UBS said investors are likely to focus on interest-rate-sensitive businesses such as the custody business of subsidiary Clearstream, while some weakness is expected in equities trading./la/zb----------------------- dpa-AFX Broker - Trader News from dpa-AFX-----------------------

title: RENAULT :  Oddo BHF confirms its recommendation on the group
full_text: Oddo BHF maintains its Outperform rating on Renault shares, with an unchanged target price of 55 euros. The analyst reports that yesterday, Renault organized an event on the 'Software-Defined Vehicle', a new architecture that places software at the heart of vehicle development.  Expected in 2026, SDV should enable Renault to gain in agility (shorter development cycles), productivity (25% reduction in R&D costs), and value (objective of 2 pts gain in residual value)", estimates Oddo BHF. For the analysts, 'Renault is presenting a software strategy that is pragmatic, with a hybrid approach based on both internal and external skills (role of architect), and a concept that aims above all to deliver productivity gains without committing to revenue prospects that are still uncertain'.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: OVHCLOUD :  Stifel lowers its target price
full_text: Stifel reaffirms its 'hold' recommendation on OVHcloud, but lowers its target price from €18 to €11, believing that pricing and cost control need to be improved for the cloud computing service provider.Rather than struggling to break even at EBIT level, OVH should theoretically show EBIT margins at the top end of the 10-20% range, given its business model', the broker judges.Stifel nevertheless believes that while outgoing shareholders and eroded confidence should impose a ceiling on the share price, 'the free cash flow yield from the installed base could limit the downside risk'.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: Nacon: growth prospects reaffirmed
full_text: Nacon gained ground on the Paris stock exchange on Tuesday after promising a 2023-2024 fiscal year rich in editorial activity, with some twenty games to be released, compared with 13 in the previous fiscal year.The video game group points out that the first half of the year will see the release of the eagerly awaited 'The Lord of the Rings Gollum', as well as 'RoboCop: Rogue City', 'Cricket24' and 'Rugby24', the official game of the Rugby World Cup, which will take place in September.On the strength of these forthcoming releases, Nacon reaffirms its confidence in its strong growth prospects for fiscal 2023-24.For the full 2022-2023 fiscal year, which ended in March, sales came in at 156.4 million euros, up 0.3% despite the postponement of several major games.In terms of earnings, the company says it anticipates at this stage a decline in operating income before non-recurring items compared with the previous year, while operating income and net income are up.Citing a "low" valuation and speculative interest in the stock, analysts at Invest Securities this morning reiterated their buy recommendation on the share, with a price target raised from 3.3 to 3.5 euros.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: Carmat: financing horizon finally extended
full_text: Carmat announced last night that it had extended its financing horizon to mid-October 2023, thanks to a non-dilutive €13.2 million financing package obtained from the French government.This line of funds, concluded as part of the 'France 2030' investment plan, is designed to support the company in increasing its production capacity for Aeson artificial hearts, with the aim of raising it to 1,000 units per year within five years.The financing consists of a grant of 7.9 million euros and a repayable advance of 5.3 million euros, with a first tranche of 3.3 million to be received by the third quarter of 2023 at the latest.Subject to the project's success, repayment of the repayable advance will be made over a five-year period, starting on September 30, 2029.On the basis of the financial resources available to it, including the first tranche of 3.3 million euros, Carmat estimates that it will be able to finance its activities until mid-October 2023, without recourse to new financing.The company also states that it is continuing to work on additional financing options in order to extend its financial visibility beyond this horizon.In a reaction note, analysts at Degroof Petercam describe the announcement as a "breath of fresh air" for the company, leading them to renew their buy recommendation on the stock, with an adjusted target price of 21 euros.The announcement puts an end to several weeks of uncertainty, as the group had indicated in February that several financing options were being explored, while highlighting a "difficult" environment.Listed on the Paris Bourse, Carmat shares were down 0.3% late Tuesday morning.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. full_text: Vivendi has announced sales of €2.29 billion for Q1 2023, up 3.3% year-on-year, including a 2% increase at constant exchange rates and scope of consolidation.UBS believes that sales are in line with last quarter's figure, and confirms its buy recommendation on the stock, with a target of 15.4 E.' title: GECINA :  Invest Securities raises its price target
full_text: Invest Securities confirms its buy rating on Gecina shares, with a price target raised from 116 to 118 euros, as Gecina published Q1 2023 rents up sharply by +7.3% on a like-for-like basis.  In particular, office space saw its occupancy rate rise sharply by +340bp year-on-year to 94.5%, a level more in line with the asset typology, accompanied by an impressive +31% reversion on Paris assets (66% of office space)", reports the analyst. Invest Securities points out that the property company has reiterated its 2023 RNR target of between E5.80 and E5.90 per share in 2023, i.e. an increase of between +4.3% and +6.1%.  The excellent debt profile, the positive net contribution of the upcoming pipeline and the ramp-up of indexations (+5.0% on average according to our estimates) should, in our opinion, enable us to easily reach our target (5.92E/share according to our estimates)", concludes Invest. title: Getlink: up sharply after positive analysis
full_text: The Getlink share ended the day up by over 4%, on the back of a positive analysis.Goldman Sachs on Monday raised its recommendation on Getlink shares to "buy", with a target price of €20.In a note published in the morning, analysts at the American bank acknowledged that the group's traffic had recently deteriorated, but said they expected the downturn to slow in the coming months.The business could also benefit from a forthcoming warming of trade relations between the UK and the European Union and/or an improvement in the British economic situation, the firm believes.The Eurotunnel operator, which competes with more carbon-intensive rivals, could ultimately benefit from the fact that airlines and ferries will have to pay for their CO2 in Europe from 2024, Goldman concludes.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: Sodexo: share price down after downgrade by RBC
full_text: Sodexo shares were down on the Paris Bourse on Monday, penalized by a recommendation downgrade by analysts at Royal Bank of Canada.The Canadian bank's teams announced this morning that they had lowered their recommendation from 'outperform' to 'in-line performance', due to a risk/return profile deemed 'better balanced'.At 3:30pm, the catering group's share price was down 0.5% in a stable Paris market, although this did not prevent it from posting a 9.5% rise since the start of the year.RBC analysts justify their downgrading by the stock's solid performance over the past 12 months, against a backdrop of improved operating results and the formalization of plans to float its services, benefits and rewards (BRS) subsidiary on the stock market next year.They note, however, that the foodservice group's 'patchy' operating performance record, combined with what they consider insufficient corporate governance, could limit investor interest at current price levels.Their target price has nevertheless been raised from €101 to €106.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. All rights reserved.

full_text: Degroof Petercam announced on Monday that it had initiated coverage of Aelis Farma shares, with a buy recommendation and a target price of €20.In a note published this morning, the Belgian investment house backs up its opinion with a series of elements, starting with the innovation represented by the biopharmaceutical company's therapeutic approach.In particular, the Brussels-based firm points to the promise of its cannabis addiction treatment and its treatment for cognitive disorders, including those associated with Down's syndrome.Degroof Petercam points out that its proprietary technology platform could be extended to other indications, suggesting that one of its projects could potentially become a 'blockbuster', i.e. a drug generating sales of over a billion dollars a year.The brokerage firm thus describes an "attractive investment opportunity", with a potential upside of 40%, as it values the company at around 250 million euros, or 20 euros a share.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: VIVENDI :  Oddo BHF confirms its recommendation on the stock
full_text: Oddo BHF confirms its 'outperform' rating on Vivendi shares, with an unchanged target price of 13.5 euros. The analyst reports that Vivendi this morning published Q1 sales in line with its expectations, noting "the good performance of Gameloft and also of Canal+ in France in pay TV, which is benefiting from recent price increases". As Vivendi holds its AGM this morning, Oddo BHF hopes that information will be shared on the next strategic milestones. In particular, the broker is keeping a close eye on the prospects for the sale of Editis to CMI, particularly in terms of timing and price. The group could also provide information on its capital strategy, in particular on the timing for the cancellation of its shares.  Depending on the company's approach (ambitious or conservative), we could draw conclusions on the cash envelope that could be dedicated to share buybacks", says Oddo BHF. title: Veolia: share price up, analyst's opinion raised
full_text: Veolia gained nearly 1% in Paris, as Deutsche Bank raised its recommendation on the stock from 'hold' to 'buy' on Friday, citing valuation issues in particular.The research firm, which also raised its target from 24 to 33 euros, acknowledges that the environmental services group could be a victim of the economic slowdown, but says it is confident in the trajectory of its results.The analyst also believes that the company could benefit from inflationary pressures, as nearly 70% of its contracts, notably with municipalities, are indexed to inflation.And although only 15% of its sales come from cyclical businesses, Veolia shares have recently performed like a cyclical stock, argues Deutsche Bank, which attributes this phenomenon to the resilience of the European economy and the downturn in energy prices.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. All rights reserved.

title: EssilorLuxottica: up sharply, a broker's opinion
full_text: EssilorLuxottica is the biggest riser on the CAC40, with a gain of almost 5.5%, following last night's announcement of consolidated sales of 6,151 million euros for the first quarter of 2023, up 8.6% at constant exchange rates compared with sales for the first quarter of 2022.Against this backdrop, Oddo BHF is maintaining its "outperform" rating on the stock, with a price target raised from €192 to €195.The analyst points out that sales came in +4% above expectations, and above all reflects a significant re-acceleration in growth.' In its main markets, the Group benefited from its premium positioning and the very good performance of frames with luxury brands (sunglasses again outperformed in Europe and Asia this quarter), while in Asia it also recorded the effects of China's recovery, which were clearly visible in February and March", notes the analyst.Against this backdrop, Oddo BHF has raised its forecasts for Q2 from +3.4% to +6.4%, for Q3 from +3.4% to +4.2% and for Q4 from +5.5% to +6.4%, resulting in y/y cc growth for the year now expected at 6.3% versus +4.0% previously.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: CARMILA :  Invest Securities slightly reduces its target
full_text: Invest Securitiesmaintains its Buy rating on Carmila shares, with a price target reduced from 18 to 17.8 euros.  Operating data to the end of March show a degree of resilience, despite a theoretically unpromising context for discretionary consumption. In fact, footfall is up +5% year-on-year, and sales are up +10%, well above indexation (+4.1%)", stresses the analyst. What's more, despite already high indexation in 2022 (+3.2%), the real estate company managed to extract a positive reversion (+2.9%). Thanks to indexation, net rents finally rose by +5.5% (no organic growth communicated), reports Invest. In this context, "the tone of the published data seems positive to us, even if we will remain vigilant regarding the impact of bankruptcies, which is more explicit at Mercialys", concludes the broker. title: ESSILORLUXOTTICA :  Oddo BHF raises its target
full_text: Oddo BHF maintains its 'outperform' rating on EssilorLuxottica shares, with its target price raised from €192 to €195. First-quarter sales came in at 6151 ME, representing growth of 9.7% on a reported basis and 8.6% cc. This is +4% above expectations, and above all reflects a significant reacceleration in growth.'In its main markets, the Group benefited from its premium positioning and the very good performance of frames for luxury brands (sunglasses outperformed Europe and Asia again this quarter), while in Asia it also recorded the effects of China's recovery, which were clearly visible in February and March', notes the analyst.Against this backdrop, Oddo BHF has raised its forecasts for Q2 from +3.4% to +6.4%, for Q3 from +3.4% to +4.2% and for Q4 from +5.5% to +6.4%, resulting in y/y cc growth for the year now expected at 6.3% versus +4.0% previously. title: PUBLICIS :  Oddo BHF raises its target price
full_text: Oddo BHF maintains its 'neutral' rating on Publicis shares, with its target price raised from €69 to €73. The research firm reports that momentum remains 'solid in Q2', but that its EBIT expectations are broadly unchanged.  We believe that the Group's valuation is now reasonable (PE 2023 of ~12x) in view of the risks of a slowdown from H2 2023 onwards", stresses the broker. Oddo BHF reports that for Q2, the Group expects organic growth of between 3% and 5%, with Epsilon and Sapient outperforming. On this basis, Publicis expects annual organic growth to be between 4% and 5% (versus 3% to +5%). For its part, the research consultancy is now forecasting +4.5% versus +3.4% for 2023. In particular, we have slightly raised our expectations for Q2 (+4.7%e) and Q3 (+4.8%e). For the time being, we remain cautious on Q4 (+1.9%e)', adds the analyst. full_text: FRANKFURT (dpa-AFX Broker) - DZ Bank lowered the fair value for Sixt ordinary shares to 122 euros from 135 euros and left its rating at "hold". title: Profit-taking at Nagarro - No impetus from the capital market day
full_text: FRANKFURT (dpa-AFX Broker) - Investors cashed in on Nagarro shares on Thursday. The papers of the IT service provider fell by around 2 percent to 103.60 euros by the afternoon. The small cap index SDax fell by 0.46 percent.      Most recently, the shares had benefited from the presentation of the financial figures for 2022 and the announcement of a share buyback. On Thursday, the focus was on the IT service provider's first capital market day. On this occasion, Nagarro wants to present its future corporate strategy, the expert Martin Comtesse from the analysis firm Jefferies had already emphasized on Monday.      But with Nagarro now just like with the capital market meetings of the dialysis provider Fresenius Medical Care and the car rental company Sixt in this week the hoped for positive news could have failed to materialize, a trader justified the price losses.       Market expert Andreas Lipkow added: "Some profit-taking can be seen in the shares of Nagarro." After the price increases of the last trading days, the price development lost some momentum./la/he----------------------- dpa-AFX Broker - Trader News from dpa-AFX-----------------------

title: OVHCLOUD :  Morgan Stanley lowers guidance
full_text: Morgan Stanley, which has an "underweight" recommendation on OVHcloud, lowered its target price on Thursday from €10.4 to €9.7 in the wake of yesterday's first-half results.According to the research firm, this performance reflects not only the slowdown in corporate capital spending, but also the effect of inflationary pressures, in particular the rise in electricity prices.According to the analyst, the growth opportunity represented by the cloud market remains intact, but achieving the targets set for 2025 - sales growth of around 25% for an adjusted operating margin of around 42% - could prove difficult.Morgan Stanley points out that it is not the only one to consider the achievement of these forecasts complicated, since the consensus is now for annual sales growth close to 19% for an operating margin of around 40%.The professional adds that after a fall of over 30% last year, OVH shares are currently down 35% this year.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: Credit Suisse Raises Target for Eon to 12.70 Euros - 'Outperform'

title: Abivax: no trend after unsurprising results
full_text: Abivax shares were trading on a hesitant note on the Paris Bourse on Thursday, following the publication of annual results deemed by analysts to be no great surprise.Shortly before 12:00 p.m., the biotech company's shares advanced by 0.9%, after having fallen by 7% during the morning.This morning, Abivax reported an operating loss of 56.6 million euros for the 2022 financial year, compared with -42.6 million euros in 2021, as a result of increased R&D investment and general and administrative expenses.In a reaction note, Degroof Petercam's teams describe the publication as "unsurprising".The only highlight is the announcement of an extension of financial visibility until the second quarter of 2024", says the Brussels-based brokerage firm.Abivax, which states that its cash consumption is currently around seven million euros per month, points out that its capital increase of 130 million euros subscribed to in February ensures its financing until the end of the second quarter of 2024.Analysts at Degroof Petercam, who have a buy recommendation on the stock, say they have adjusted their price target for the shares from 13.5 to 16.2 euros.Thanks in particular to promising clinical results in rectocolitis hemorrhagica, Abivax shares have gained over 99% since the start of the year.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. All rights reserved.

title: EURONEXT :  Morgan Stanley returns to 'weight in line
full_text: Morgan Stanley resumed coverage of Euronext shares on Thursday, with a 'weight in line' recommendation and a price target of 93.5 euros.In a study of European stock market operators, the analyst acknowledges that the stock's valuation may seem attractive, but believes that its cyclical nature is likely to limit its immediate upside potential.Morgan Stanley expects that economic uncertainties will lead issuers to postpone their projects, a factor likely to penalize the Group, which is highly dependent on cash markets and IPOs.As for the integration of Borsa Italiana, it seems to be progressing well, continues the analyst, who nevertheless considers that the synergies of the operation are already well integrated into the share price.As for potential accretive acquisitions, the professional acknowledges that they have the potential to support the value, but points out that recent financial news seems to have scalded investor enthusiasm for operations deemed too risky.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: L'ORÉAL :  Oddo BHF raises its price target
full_text: Oddo BHF maintains its 'neutral' rating on L'Oréal shares, with a price target raised from 346 to 387 euros. The analyst reports that L'Oréal's quarterly sales came in nearly 9% ahead of expectations, "the magnitude of the surprise is unprecedented in memory", stresses the broker. Sales came to 10,380 ME, representing organic growth of 13%.  L'Oréal is without doubt the quality pure player with the most successful model among European and US Food Spirits HPC players. We believe that this superiority is strongly reflected in the PE multiples (36x 2023e)', judges Oddo BHF. Against this backdrop, the analyst revises his EPS forecasts for 2023 and beyond by 3% following Q1, which now leads him to anticipate organic growth of 10% over 2023. title: Sartorius fall - 'First quarter much worse than expected'
full_text: FRANKFURT (dpa-AFX Broker) - Sartorius shares, which have been weak since February, face further trouble on Thursday following quarterly figures. At broker Lang & Schwarz, the shares of the laboratory equipment manufacturer slipped 4.9 percent to 367.50 euros in pre-market trading. In Xetra trading, this would be the lowest price since the beginning of January.      A trader said that Sartorius had significantly missed expectations in all key figures. The currency-adjusted drop in order intake by almost one-third was shocking. Analysts had already anticipated a weaker first quarter, but not to this extent, the trader said.      In the first quarter of the year, the DAX-listed group fell well short of its prior-year figures. Because customers reduced their inventories and the corona business now hardly makes a contribution, sales declined. In addition, higher costs resulted in weaker profitability./ajx/mis----------------------- dpa-AFX Broker - Trader News from dpa-AFX-----------------------

title: Fresh investor money does not make Tui more valuable
full_text: FRANKFURT (dpa-AFX) - Despite a growing appetite for travel in the wake of the Corona crisis, the share price of tourism group Tui is going downhill. In the wake of a long-announced capital increase to repay state aid, the securities went down to a record low of 5.836 euros on Tuesday. The fresh money from investors was practically pulverized in recent weeks.      By issuing around 329 million new shares, Tui raised 1.8 billion euros as planned, according to a spokesman. The travel company got rid of the last nine percent of these shares on Tuesday with a so-called short placement - at 5.60 euros per share. On the stock exchange, the old shares were last traded above the 6 euro mark in the afternoon at 6.41 euros. By way of comparison, five years ago the price was more than 60 euros, adjusted for the various capital measures, according to Bloomberg.      Adding up the value of the shares, which will in future total slightly more than half a billion, the Tui Group is now valued on the stock exchange at a total of just under 3.3 billion euros. This is practically the same as at the beginning of December, before Tui announced the capital increase that has now been completed. This was also preceded by a consolidation of the previous shares at a ratio of ten to one: Those who previously held ten shares now only had one. Five years ago, the Group was worth just under twelve billion euros; before the Corona pandemic at the end of 2019, it was worth around seven billion euros.      Capital increases are now nothing new for Tui shareholders. After all, the current one was already the fourth since the beginning of the Corona crisis. At that time, travel restrictions as a result of the pandemic had temporarily brought the travel business to a complete standstill, and the German state saved the travel giant from going under with financial injections worth billions.      In the meantime, the vacation business is up and running again, and Tui intends to use the money from the current capital increase to repay the last of the aid money. This should significantly shrink the company's mountain of debt and thus its future interest burden.      However, industry expert Jamie Rollo of investment bank Morgan Stanley advised investors last week to continue avoiding Tui shares. His colleague Oliver Wojahn of Alsterresearch, on the other hand, saw the recent drop in the share price as an opportunity to enter the market. He attributes a price target of 18 euros to the papers. To achieve this, the price would have to roughly triple from the current perspective.      One crux of the capital raising this time was the exclusion of Tui's long-time major shareholder Alexei Mordashov, who before the capital increase still held slightly more than 30 percent of Tui shares. The Russian oligarch had played a major role in previous capital measures, helping to save the Group during the pandemic.      However, as a result of the Russian war of aggression against Ukraine, he is no longer allowed to invest in Tui. This is because the EU had placed Mordashov on its sanctions list at the end of February 2022. According to voting rights notifications, he transferred the lion's share of his shares to his wife Marina Mordashova via an investment company.      According to Tui, however, this transfer is "pending invalid" - because the German Federal Ministry of Economics initiated an investigation under the Foreign Trade and Payments Act just over a year ago. The capital increase significantly reduces the share of the Russian investor.      Tui's management tried to allay investors' concerns at the beginning of April with the news that it would itself participate in the capital increase. Accordingly, the members of the Executive Board have exercised their subscription rights in full. Supervisory Board Chairman Dieter Zetsche reportedly subscribed to 8600 new shares, and with around 28,800 shares he is already the largest shareholder of all members of the Executive Board and Supervisory Board./stw/zb/he

title: Virbac: at half-mast after its quarterly trading update
full_text: Virbac has lost almost 3%, making it one of the biggest decliners on the SBF120, the day after the animal health group announced sales of 314.8 million euros for its first quarter 2023, down slightly by 1.3% at constant exchange rates.This sales figure was more than 5% below Oddo BHF's estimate, which downgraded its opinion on the share from 'outperform' to 'neutral', in the absence of upside potential in relation to its price target maintained at 293 euros.Nevertheless, the research firm says that it considers the sluggishness of sales to be temporary, and that it remains "fundamentally positive", as animal health offers a defensive profile in its French midcap healthcare universe.Virbac has confirmed its full-year forecasts at this stage, attributing the decline in sales to an "unfavorable base effect in a context of market slowdown", and secondarily to inventory effects observed in distribution at the end of 2022.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: Sopra Steria: back towards all-time highs, HSBC in support
full_text: Sopra Steria shares are back towards their all-time highs on Tuesday on the Paris Bourse, supported by a favorable recommendation.Alongside giants SAP and Dassault Systèmes, the stock is among the European technology stocks that HSBC analysts are today recommending as Buy in a sector study.The British bank, which renews its buy recommendation and price target of 235 euros on Sopra, highlights the technology group's low stock market valuation and resilient business profile.Its exposure to the banking sector remains one of the highest in our services coverage area, but is mainly focused on multi-year contracts which do not appear to be under threat", says HSBC.The stock is currently gaining 2.7% after reaching a daily peak of 196.3 euros, not far from its all-time high of 198.3 euros. It is one of the strongest performers in the SBF 120 index.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. All rights reserved.

full_text: On Tuesday, Barclays raised its recommendation on Orange from 'in-line weighted' to 'overweight', with a price target raised from 12 to 13.5 euros.In a sector note, the research firm justifies its decision by pointing to the continuing improvement in prices of offers in France, as illustrated by the recent increases announced by Bouygues and SFR.But with almost 65% of its intrinsic value derived from France, it is Orange that is most likely to benefit from this buoyant pricing environment, Barclays believes.The analyst also expects the telecom operator's profitability to continue its upward trajectory, with return on capital employed (ROCE) rising from 5.7% in 2021 to 6.1% in 2022.By 2025, this should be around 7%, according to Barclays' projections.Finally, the stock is attractively valued, with a discount to its peers in terms of shareholder free cash flow (SFCF) multiples.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. full_text: Berenberg announced on Tuesday that it had lowered its target for Soitec from 205 to 200 euros, while maintaining its buy recommendation on the stock.Although the semiconductor materials specialist recently revised its outlook downwards to 2026, the quality of the company's case remains intact from a long-term perspective, according to the analyst in a note released this morning.Admittedly, the forecasts unveiled for the 2023/2024 financial year are below expectations, but they are nonetheless less bad than the market might have feared, he adds.After the slowdown in growth expected for the 2023/2024 financial year, growth should make a comeback thereafter, promises the intermediary, who believes that the share's valuation remains attractive in view of the growth expected from the 2024/2025 financial year onwards.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: VIVENDI :  Oddo confirms its target price for the share
full_text: Oddo maintains its 'outperform' rating on Vivendi shares, with a target price of 13.5 euros. With the group due to publish its Q1 sales on April 24, Oddo expects growth of 4% (or consolidated sales of €2,315 million) for the quarter, a slight slowdown compared with Q4, "which reflects a logical slowdown at Havas"According to the analyst, the group is expected to renew its two main resolutions, namely the possibility of buying back 10% of its capital on the market and launching a public stock buyback tender offer for up to 50% of its capital.  This event could provide an opportunity to obtain further details on the strategic agenda, i.e. the timing of the sale of Editis and the finalization of the Lagardère acquisition, and above all the company's plan for share cancellations, which are expected to run from July to September", stresses Oddo. The broker also points out that Bolloré could cross the threshold of 30% of Vivendi's capital. Our scenario remains an offer by Bolloré for Vivendi (and not a sale of shares - although this is entirely possible)', it concludes. Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: AIRBUS :  Oddo confirms its recommendation on the stock
full_text: Oddo maintains its 'outperform' rating on Airbus Group shares, with an unchanged target price of 145 euros. With the aircraft manufacturer due to publish its Q1 results on the evening of May 3 - results which should reflect weak deliveries - Oddo models an adjusted EBIT of €716m, on sales of €10.9 bn, representing a margin of 6.6% (-396 bp)."The Q1 publication should not reveal any surprises, but will demonstrate that the contribution of additional volume will offer operating leverage despite inflationary pressures", stresses the broker. According to the analyst, most of the margin decline is attributable to Airbus Commercial, a division which should see its EBIT fall by 50.1%, to 532 ME.'While most players are reporting a gradual improvement in the health of the supply chain, we are waiting for concrete evidence that Airbus is regaining control of its chain', says Oddo. title: Capgemini: share price down, analyst lowers target
full_text: Capgemini lost nearly 3% in Paris this morning, as Oddo lowered its price target on the stock from 226 to 223 euros, while retaining its 'outperform' rating.With Capgemini due to publish its Q4 sales on May 4 (before market opening), Oddo anticipates a slowdown in organic growth going beyond mere base effects.The research firm is thus cautiously targeting org. growth. title: Berenberg sees turnaround at Teamviewer - 'Buy'.
full_text: HAMBURG (dpa-AFX) - Private bank Berenberg expects a turnaround for the better at Teamviewer after two challenging years. In a study available on Monday, Berenberg analyst Gustav Froberg pointed to a recovery in business with medium-sized and small companies (SMB business) at the MDax software group. This recovery is being overlooked by many investors, he said, as they are far too fixated on the problems of the past.      As a result, Froberg upgraded Teamviewer shares from "hold" to "buy" and also raised the price target sharply from 14.50 to 21.00 euros. This is the highest price target of all analysts covered by dpa-AFX who cover Teamviewer. At the start of the week, the stock benefited enormously from this and moved to the top of the MDax. The recovery in the share price, which had been faltering since mid-February, gained fresh momentum after the stock climbed above 16 euros. There were already signs of recovery in Teamviewer's SMB business in the final quarter, as the figures for 2022 showed some time ago.      In general, Froberg praised Teamviewer's customer structure: large customers (enterprise customers) with larger contracts than those of SMB customers represented twenty percent of total billings, i.e., billed revenues, but less than one percent of the total customer base. The expert sees great potential for future price increases here. He also rated margins and free cash flow as sustainable.      Teamviewer was one of the big beneficiaries of the Corona pandemic, but then took on too much, among other things, with an expensive sponsorship agreement with the English soccer club Manchester United. At the end of 2022, however, Teamviewer negotiated an exit option from the expensive shirt sponsorship deal with the Premier League club. Froberg believes that a possible earlier exit could provide further tailwind for the Teamviewer share.      Analyst Froberg sees additional price drivers in the upcoming annual report for the first quarter of the year at the beginning of May, as well as in the presentation of figures for the second quarter in August. Froberg believes that investors will increasingly recognize the turnaround at Teamviewer. He therefore sees this as an attractive time to buy the stock, especially since Teamviewer is one of the most favorably valued shares in the industry in Europe.      With a "Buy" recommendation, Berenberg sees a sustainable price potential of more than 15 percent for the stock over a twelve-month period.      Analyzing institute Berenberg./niw/mis/men  Publication of the original study: 14.04.2023 / 16:29 / GMT First dissemination of the original study: Date not specified in study / Time not specified in study / Time zone not specified in study

title: Morphosys rise on Tradegate after study data
full_text: FRANKFURT (dpa-AFX Broker) - The shares of Morphosys have increased significantly on Monday after study data pre-market. They rose on the trading platform Tradegate compared to the Xetra close on Friday last just under one percent to 19.205 euros, after the price had climbed in early trading to 19.595 euros. The biotech company announced final five-year follow-up results from a Phase II trial of the drug Monjuvi plus lenalidomide (L-MIND), which was positively assessed by two traders. Both expect prices to rise at the start of trading.      After a downward slide between mid-February and around the beginning of April, the share is now back on the road to recovery and has recouped the losses it suffered. In the past seven trading days alone, the stock has gained 30 percent. However, this has done little to change the long-term negative trend. Since the multi-year high of just over 146 euros in January 2020, the share price has fallen by 90 percent despite the recent recovery./ck/zb

full_text: While maintaining its 'hold' recommendation, Stifel has raised its target price for Eiffage from 107 to 112 euros, seeing a series of factors that should continue to support the stock and the sector as a whole in 2023."In the absence of any discernible Group-specific catalyst, and being slightly more exposed to a recession, we expect Eiffage to lag behind its direct contracting peers, although 2023 should at worst be a resilient year", he judges however."While we appreciate a measured and patient approach, Eiffage's strategy may be too conservative for its own good", adds the broker, hoping nevertheless that an adjustment in valuations will "crystallize new M&A opportunities".Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: ALSTOM :  Deutsche Bank downgrades its recommendation
full_text: On Friday, Deutsche Bank downgraded its recommendation on Alstom from 'buy' to 'hold', following the announcement of the departure of the Group's CFO, Laurent Martinez.Orange said last night that it had appointed Laurent Martinez as Executive Director in charge of finance, performance and development, a position he will take up in September.According to Deutsche Bank, this departure is likely to raise a number of concerns regarding both (1) the maintenance of current financial targets and (2) a potential change in relations with the Moody's agency.The process of integrating Bombardier Transportation looks set to be a complex one, likely to take several years, which leads us to wait until Alstom's management team is definitively in place before taking another look at the dossier", concludes the analyst.His price target remains 30 euros.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: AIR FRANCE-KLM :  Oddo confirms its target price
full_text: Oddo maintains its 'neutral' rating on Air France-KLM shares, with an unchanged target price of 2.1 euros. With the publication of the 1st quarter scheduled for May 5, the research firm anticipates 'a continuation of the trend visible since the 2nd half of 2022, with an expected yield Network up 23% on the 2019 level'. The broker reports that the rise accelerated at the end of the quarter, 'which bodes well for the direction of Q2'. Oddo models an operating loss of ME 316 (vs. ME 350 in Q1 2022) on sales of ME 6,422 (+44.5%), and targets FY 23 EBIT of ME 1,508. In addition, the analyst anticipates an Adjusted FCF of 334 ME, which would reduce net debt to just under 6 MdsE (vs. 6.3 MdsE at end December 2022).  The pricing environment shows no signs of slowing down (apart from cargo, where the decline in yield is, at this stage, in line with our estimates), which could offer an upside for Q2 and Q3, but we would like further assurances on the evolution of unit costs", concludes Oddo. title: KLÉPIERRE :  Barclays upgrades its opinion twice
full_text: Barclays announced on Thursday that it had directly upgraded its recommendation on Klépierre shares from 'underweight' to 'overweight', with a price target raised from 22 to 24 euros.In a note devoted to the European real estate sector, Barclays analysts point out that Klépierre has emerged from the Covid crisis with occupancy rates close to their pre-pandemic levels.Above all, they point out, the property company has succeeded in renewing 26% of its retail space thanks to the arrival of new occupants, while maintaining occupancy costs at 13%.While acknowledging that the Group's occupancy rates could prove volatile this year, due to the cost increases that retailers are having to undergo, the analysts explain that they expect this indicator to stabilize overall.While 50% of analysts covering the stock have a negative recommendation on Klépierre, Barclays considers that the market is currently underestimating the company's relative resistance to a possible economic slowdown.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: IDI  :  FY22: IDI in a solid stand amidst an adverse environment
full_text:
FY22: IDI in a solid stand amidst an adverse environmentEARNINGS/SALES RELEASESAfter a record-breaking FY2021, IDI enjoyed another solid and active year with NAV per share up 12%. This strong momentum was driven both by the robust operating performance of its portfolio companies against an inflationary backdrop (i) and disposals at attractive terms (ii). 2022 proved to be a milestone year in the equity story of IDI, which has decided to strengthen its presence in third-party management with the acquisition of Omnes’ private equity and private debt activities under the newly created entity, IdiCo. While IDI is resilient in the face of macroeconomic headwinds, prudence remains the watchword. FACTKey FY22 figuresIDI’s NAV reached €673m at the end of FY22. The NAV per share stood at €89.45, up 12% yoy, corresponding to a significant 40.9% discount to NAV based on the current share price.  
Although below the €126.2m achieved in the peak year 2021, IDI recorded an impressive net result of €80.4m, well above the €32.4m of 2020.
The company’s total liquidity position stood at €124m at the end of 2021, down 13.8% yoy, with €60m of credit lines (€30m drawn in Q1 23) and a €5m overdraft facility.
In 2022, IDI completed 15 transactions including 1 acquisition, 10 build-ups, 2 disposals, 1 reinvestment and the Omnes deal.   
The major strategic transaction with Omnes was completed on March 23, 2023. IDI acquired 40% in Omnes’ renewable energy, venture capital and co-investment activities, and a 100% stake in IdiCo which regroups Omnes’ small, lower, mid cap private equity and private debt activities.
In terms of dividends, IDI has proposed a dividend of €2.5 per share or 2.8% of NAV and 4.57% of its average share price for 2022.ANALYSISStrong performance in a hostile private equity environment
While our HoldCo universe has not been spared by the equity market downturn and the hostile 2022 environment, IDI has proven resilient with NAV up 12% yoy to €673m (vs €611m) or €89.45 per share. A notable feat in today’s climate explained by (i) the excellent operational performances of the portfolio companies in the face of inflationary pressures and  (ii) the active investment activity in 2022. 
IDI’s investment activity was buoyant in 2022, with 15 deals completed, including one acquisition, ten build-ups, two disposals, one reinvestment and the signature of the agreement with Omnes. In terms of exits also, IDI is thriving regardless of the current environment, with notably the sale of the SaaS software publisher Groupe Positive (ex-Sarbacane), which allowed IDI to record a cash-on-cash multiple of 3.1x and a net IRR of more than 70%, and the sale of Formalian for a multiple of 3x and an IRR of 32%. The healthy performance of the Private Equity business in Europe allowed the HoldCo to post a significant result from investment activities of €94.2 million, below the €146 million recorded in the exceptional year of 2021, but well above the €40 million recorded in 2020.
A new era impelled by the Omnes acquisition
If 2022 was a busy year for investments, 2023 is also shaping up nicely for IDI, which has already completed 4 deals: the external growth of Talis Education into the Fore group and 2 disposals, including that of Freeland, the French leader in services to the self-employed, to MML Capital, enabling IDI to achieve a solid investment multiple of 2.2x and an IRR of c. 24% in less than 4 years.
The biggest deal in 2023, however, remained the acquisition of a significant stake (>40%) in Omnes’ renewable energy, venture capital and co-investment businesses (representing €5bn of AuM) and 100% of IdiCo, a newly-created entity that combines Omnes’ private equity and private debt businesses. IdiCo is designed to be IDI’s new European third-party management arm, managing €1bn of AuM. The transaction, which closed on March 23, 2023 instead of in the expected Q4-22, totally transforms IDI in that it will double the size of IDI’s third-party management business to €1.5 billion in assets under management (including $620 million for Emerging Markets IDI). Although no figures have been disclosed, the deal will change IDI’s financial statements in terms of revenues, with stable management fees and some performance fees on IdiCo’s fee-paying AuM. In terms of costs, we expect the transaction to result in an increase in personnel costs owing to some 30 additional people according to our estimates. We see the transaction as a way for IDI to leverage its size in investment opportunities. Details of the transaction and integration dates have not yet been disclosed although, according to sources in Les Echos, Omnes has an enterprise value of around €120m.
Looking ahead to 2023 
In terms of outlook, despite the acquisition of Omnes, IDI’s core business remains direct investment in SMEs/ITCs, with a target of 12 to 15 companies in its portfolio. The company does not limit itself in terms of sectors but rather looks for opportunities. In view of its growing balance sheet, IDI expects to invest in tickets above €25m with co-investments of up to €100m.
Although the macroeconomic context is unfavorable, IDI can pride itself on a portfolio of quality companies with a degree of pricing power. Moreover, in an environment of rising interest rates and difficult financing, IDI has the financial strength and privileged relationships to face the challenges.  Valuation-wise as well, the HoldCo looks attractive with a 41% discount to NAV at present. Finally, we see the acquisition of Omnes as being positive for IDI, which will be able to (i) diversify its revenues (ii) pocket a steady stream of income from stable management fees (iii) position itself on larger tickets with a scale effect (iv) share competencies between IDI and Omnes managers and (v) create synergies in the field of ESG. However, even if IDI is well positioned to meet the challenges ahead, caution remains our watchword for the comprehensive PE industry as the tightening in financial condition at a precipitated clip in 2022 will inevitably take its toll in 2023.
Making progress on the ESG front
On the ESG front, IDI has strengthened its commitment with the creation of an ESG committee at the supervisory board level. 2022 marked the formalization of IDI’s ESG approach, which is integrated into the entire investment cycle from due diligence, to the investment decision and the investment agreement, to the management of IDI’s holdings. Finally, in line with the objectives of the PRI, to which IDI has become a signatory, IDI is in the process of setting up an effective reporting system. By 2023, IDI intends to establish its first carbon footprint (Scopes 1, 2 and 3) measurements at both the holding and the portfolio company level. IMPACTWe will revalue the underlying companies to estimate our NAV with the revision of the listed peer group multiples. We will incorporate the FY22 numbers into our model and roll forward our estimates to 2025 taking into account the Omnes acquisition which brings a significant twist to the original business model (third party money, more staff). The strong FY22 results continue to support our positive stance on the stock even if we remain dubious about private equity players in the prevailing context.

title: BASF struggles with 50-day and 100-day line after key data

title: CARREFOUR  :  Barclays raises its target price
full_text: On Wednesday, Barclays raised its price target for Carrefour from €20 to €22 in anticipation of a good start to the retailer's financial year.The research firm - which maintains an 'overweight' recommendation on the stock - says it expects sales to accelerate in the first quarter, driven by both inflationary pressures and market share gains.Barclays says it expects like-for-like growth of 5.5% for hypermarkets, 7.5% for supermarkets and 9.5% for convenience stores over the first three months of the year.More generally, the analyst praises the French retail giant's strategic direction.We believe that Carrefour is continuing to implement the right strategy by increasing its retailer-brand penetration, transferring underperforming stores to franchisees, reducing its cost structure and developing new profitable growth channels, such as retail media", he explains.We believe that this strategy not only benefits the group's growth prospects and profit margins, but also improves its risk profile", concludes Barclays.Carrefour is scheduled to publish its first-quarter sales on Tuesday, April 25, after the close of the Paris market.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: Tui subscription rights under pressure on last trading day
full_text: LONDON/FRANKFURT (dpa-AFX) - The shares of Tui are in focus at midweek. This is because trading in the subscription rights from the travel group's capital increase ends this Wednesday. In the morning in Xetra main trading, the price of the subscription rights fell by more than a third to 1.21 euros compared to the Xetra close the previous day - continuing the strong fluctuations in trading so far.      On the London Stock Exchange, where the vast majority of subscription rights and also Tui shares are traded, the Tui share price fell by 1.6 percent to 5.77 pounds. With the start of the capital increase at the end of March, the papers had collapsed below the 10-pound mark, at the low to around 5.40 pounds.      Analyst Jamie Rollo of the investment bank Morgan Stanley had advised the previous day to continue to avoid Tui shares. The expert expects a weak reception of the new shares by investors. The sharp drop in the price of the subscription rights is likely to prove him right in this respect. The result would be a large overhang of shares, which would put latent pressure on the share price in the future, according to Rollo.      So far, the subscription rights business on the German market has been very volatile. On the first trading day on Xetra at the end of March, the price rose from 5.55 euros to as high as 6.99 euros. Subsequently, the price fell to 84 cents amid strong fluctuations. On the Thursday before the long Easter weekend, the price shot up by almost 160 percent to 2.87 euros; on Tuesday, it fell again by around 35 percent. Every trading day, an average of just under five million subscription rights changed hands on Xetra.      According to the prospectus for the capital increase, trading in subscription rights on the Frankfurt and Hanover stock exchanges ends at midday. On the London Stock Exchange, on the other hand, the securities will be traded until the close of trading./bek/gl/ngu----------------------- dpa-AFX Broker - Trader News from dpa-AFX-----------------------

title: JPMorgan leaves Scout24 at 'Overweight' - Target 63 euros
full_text: NEW YORK (dpa-AFX Broker) - U.S. bank JPMorgan left its rating for Scout24  at "Overweight" with a price target of 63 euros. Analyst Marcus Diebel addressed this year's prospects for European online retailers and service providers in an investment recommendation available on Tuesday. He attributed the best chances to classifieds portals due to their strong pricing power and additional revenue streams. For food delivery services, he was cautious, saying the potential for margin expansion is still unclear. For fashion retailers, Diebel sees the risk of slower growth in online penetration and the challenge of weaning consumers off the recent surge in discounting. His sector favorites are Scout24, Delivery Hero, Adevinta, Future and Jahez./edh/la  Publication of the original study: 10.04.2023 / 18:34 / BST First disclosure of the original study: 11.04.2023 / 00:15 / BST----------------------- dpa-AFX Broker - the Trader News from dpa-AFX-----------------------

title: JPMorgan upgrades Hellofresh and praises expansion of ready meals
full_text: NEW YORK (dpa-AFX) - Opportunities now outweigh risks at cooking box provider Hellofresh, according to U.S. bank JPMorgan. Analyst Marcus Diebel pointed to the lowered consensus estimates, expansion plans in the promising ready-to-eat (RTE) business, the attractive valuation and the limited risks for further share price losses in a study available on Tuesday.      Therefore, the expert raised the share by two investment levels from "Underweight" to "Overweight". He raised the price target from EUR 18 to EUR 27, which is almost 16 percent above the current valuation level.      Due to the reluctance of customers in the traditional business with cooking boxes, he welcomed the rapid and strategic entry of the company into the more promising RTE area, Diebel explained. The main segment around the distribution of cooking boxes had long been the main reason for his cautious assessment of the stock. To be sure, he said, some cannibalization effects between the two segments are to be expected. But average expectations, as well as his estimates, were well below management's 2025 targets, and a disappointing first half of 2023 was already generally expected, he said. After the recent decline in the share price, the risk of further losses is also within bounds. Diebel justified the new price target with his raised sales expectations.      According to the "Overweight" rating, JPMorgan expects the share to outperform the respective sector in the coming six to twelve months.  Analyzing institute JPMorgan./gl/bek/ngu  Publication of the original study: 10.04.2023 / 19:36 / BST First disclosure of the original study: 11.04.2023 / 00:15 / BST

title: SAINT-GOBAIN :  Oddo maintains its 'outperform' rating
full_text: Oddo maintains its Outperform rating on Saint-Gobain shares, with an unchanged target price of 70 euros. With Q1 results due on April 27, Oddo expects the Group to post a "slightly difficult Q1 due to a high basis of comparison".  We are expecting Q1 sales of 12,260 ME, up 2.1% (+3.6% L/L: prices +9.3%, volume -5.8%). The company's consensus has not been published, but Visible Alpha expects sales of 12.4 billion euros, close to our expectations", says the research firm.The group's guidance should remain unchanged, with Saint-Gobain targeting an increase in operating margin of between 9% and 11%, and the consensus expecting EBIT in 2023 of 4.67 billion euros and a margin of 9.4%, at the lower end of the group's guidance range.  We believe that Saint-Gobain has the potential to provide a pleasant surprise for the year, and why not an increase in the consensus earnings outlook, probably in H1," concludes the analyst. title: Air Liquide: upbeat after positive analyses

title: Goldman sees European e-car makers at a disadvantage to Tesla
full_text: NEW YORK (dpa-AFX) - U.S. investment bank Goldman Sachs sees most European manufacturers of electric cars at a technological disadvantage compared to e-car pioneer Tesla from the United States. Analyst George Galliers therefore lowered in a study presented on Thursday the price targets of numerous car stocks and downgraded the shares of BMW and Volvo Cars. Better chances he admits only the sports car manufacturers Porsche AG, Ferrari and Aston Martin, for which he increased the price targets.      So far, there is little evidence of industry-leading products from European electric car makers when considering overall powertrain efficiency, Galliers wrote. At best, efficiency can match Tesla's, but in many cases it is below it. In addition, he said, Tesla's reported gross margins (around 27 percent in 2022) are much higher than those of European manufacturers. This suggests that the technology gap could be even wider, he said.      Galliers believes that while European e-car producers can continue to compete effectively, and that their core competencies continue to offer competitive advantages. However, the European automotive industry - if it wants to retain its strong position - must in the future manufacture products that set new industry standards for powertrain efficiency, the expert urged. Because otherwise there are risks for the future. The analyst expects Tesla and Chinese manufacturers to capture market share in Europe over the next decade./edh/ajx/jha/      Analyzing institute Goldman Sachs.      Publication of the original study: 06.04.2023 / 06:02 / BST First disclosure of the original study: Date in study not specified / Time in study not specified / Time zone in study not specified.

title: Jefferies lowers target for Basler to 26 euros - 'Hold'.
full_text: NEW YORK (dpa-AFX Broker) - Analysts Jefferies cut its price target for Basler to 26 euros from 30 euros, but kept its rating at "hold." title: Neoen: share price rises, Morgan Stanley sees fewer risks
full_text: Neoen shares were up on Wednesday, benefiting from a recommendation upgrade by Morgan Stanley, which said it saw fewer risks surrounding the renewable energies specialist.After jumping nearly 3.5% during the morning, the energy company's shares gained 0.6% around 12:30 p.m., while the SBF 120 was down by around 0.2%.Morgan Stanley raised its recommendation on the stock from "underweight" to "weight in line", with a price target reduced from €33 to €32.In a research note, the financial intermediary explains that it perceives fewer downside risks surrounding the energy company now that market forecasts to 2025 have been revised and its capital increase has been finalized.While acknowledging that the stock's valuation is now less strained, the analyst stresses that it is still far from cheap, explaining that he is waiting for more visibility on the group's value-creation potential in renewable energies before being more "constructive" on the dossier.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: KERING :  Oddo raises its target price on the stock
full_text: Oddo maintains its 'neutral' rating on Kering shares, with its target price raised from €568 to €580.According to the analyst, trends at the start of the year point to contrasting evolutions, depending on geographical zones, brands and distribution channels. Oddo has slightly adjusted its forecasts for the 1st quarter, with y/y cc growth at -2% for Gucci (vs. -4% previously) and +6% for Saint Laurent (vs. +4% previously). It is also reducing its forecasts for Bottega Veneta from +4% to +1% and for Other Houses from -5% to -7%, "resulting in final group growth of -1% versus -2% previously reported", says the broker. Oddo also points out that taking into account more unfavorable exchange rates for 2023 leads to a -1% reduction in its sales estimates for 2023/2024/2025.  All in all, our new EBIT estimates are down -1%/-2% on previous estimates', says the research firm, which adds that the share is still trading at a discount of just over 30% at this stage to the LVMH sector benchmark.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com. title: Goldman raises target for Deutsche Bank to 19.50 euros - 'Buy'.
full_text: NEW YORK (dpa-AFX Broker) - U.S. investment bank Goldman Sachs raised its price target for Deutsche Bank to 19.50 euros from 19.40 euros and kept its rating at "buy." Analyst Chris Hallam referred in a study available on Wednesday to the above-average losses in the share price since the beginning of March and justified them with the problems in the banking industry and concerns about a leapfrogging of the Credit Suisse problems. At the same time, he remains confident. He updated his estimates, working into his valuation model higher overall retail banking revenues and, given rising interest rates, a higher margin. full_text: NEW YORK (dpa-AFX Broker) - U.S. investment bank Morgan Stanley cut its price target for Deutsche Telekom to 26.50 euros from 27.00 euros, but kept its rating at "overweight." title: L'ORÉAL :  Oddo remains neutral after the acquisition of Aesop
full_text: Oddo believes that the acquisition of the Aësop brand will undeniably enable L'Oréal to strengthen its operational footprint in Beauty by adding a skincare brand positioned in the premium segment with an exclusive distribution network on all continents (except Africa). Following this transaction, Oddo confirms its Neutral recommendation on the value, with a target of 346 E.' According to the press release, Aësop's EV is 2525 ME and sales have reached 537 ME in 2022, representing an EV/Sales22 of 4.7x. The Group gives no indication of the level of operating margin. But if we assume an operating margin of between 20% and 25%, this would give an EV/EBITA22e of between 19x and 23x', says Oddo.  Nevertheless, this multiple remains high, and can only be justified by growth synergies. We believe that China should be the 1st lever of synergies, given that the Aësop brand has only been present there since 2022, with the opening of a 1st point of sale, and that L'Oréal has a significant level of critical mass in China (c.20% of sales)' adds the analyst.Copyright (c) 2023 CercleFinance.com.
